snippet: The service members have found themselves reoccupying some of their old places and discovering everyday items that were left behind.
lead_paragraph: The service members have found themselves reoccupying some of their old places and discovering everyday items that were left behind.
abstract: Camp Taji journal; American forces, returning to Iraq in diminished numbers to help country repel Islamic State, have established themselves at two old bases; one is at Al Asad Air Base in Anbar Province, but at the base at Taji, about 20 miles north of Baghdad, much has been left undisturbed and seemingly frozen in time; soldiers are finding many personal items troops left behind in 2011.
headline/main: U.S. Forces, Returning to Iraq, Encounter the Things Their Comrades Carried
headline/print_headline: U.S. Forces, Returning to Iraq, Encounter the Things Their Comrades Carried

snippet: The United States military has begun looking into two instances in which coalition airstrikes against the Sunni militancy known as the Islamic State may have inadvertently hit civilians.
lead_paragraph: The United States military has begun looking into two instances in which coalition airstrikes against the Sunni militancy known as the Islamic State may have inadvertently hit civilians.
abstract: Pentagon Press Sec Rear Adm John Kirby says United States is looking into reports of civilian casualties in Iraq and Syria that possibly happened due to American-led airstrikes against Islamic State.

snippet: Hamyd Mourad, 18, suspected in an assault on the satirical newspaper Charlie Hebdo, walked into a police station northeast of Paris and gave himself up. The other suspects are two brothers, Said and Chérif Kouachi.
lead_paragraph: Hamyd Mourad, 18, suspected in an assault on the satirical newspaper Charlie Hebdo, walked into a police station northeast of Paris and gave himself up. The other suspects are two brothers, Said and Chérif Kouachi.
abstract: Masked gunmen attack Paris headquarters of satirical newspaper Charlie Hebdo, killing 12 people and traumatizing city; police carry out manhunt for suspects Said and Cherif Kouachi, while third suspect Hamyd Mourad turns himself in; reports that Kouachi brothers were born in Paris raises fear of homegrown terrorists and distrust of local Muslims.
headline/main: Terrorists Strike Charlie Hebdo Newspaper in Paris, Leaving 12 Dead
headline/print_headline: Terrorists Strike Paris Newspaper, Leaving 12 Dead
byline/contributor: Aurelien Breeden and Laure Fourquet contributed reporting from Paris, and Michael S. Schmidt from Washington.
byline/original: By DAN BILEFSKY and MAÏA de la BAUME
headline/sub: One Suspect Surrenders; Police Organize Manhunt for 2 Others

snippet: Muslims are debating why their religion is so often cited as a cause for violence and bloodshed.
lead_paragraph: Muslims are debating why their religion is so often cited as a cause for violence and bloodshed.
abstract: Horrific attacks by Islam extremists in name of their religion, like massacre in Paris, is fueling debate among Muslims over why Islam has been blamed for so much violence and murder; most scholars and followers say Islam is not any more violent than other religions, but small number of Muslims contend theology is source of extremist violence, and needs correction of its teaching.
headline/main: Raising Questions Within Islam After France Shooting
